[Maps of Sri Lanka: http://www.mapsopensource.com/images/sri-lanka-districts-map.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8300187,144

The South Asian COVID-19 situation, according to data from Worldometer (https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/) as of 9 Apr 2021 at 04:41 GMT:

Country: Total cases / Total deaths / Deaths per million population
India: 13 060 542 / 167 694 / 121
Pakistan: 710 829 / 15 229 / 68
Bangladesh: 666 132 / 9521 / 57
Nepal: 279 100 / 3038 / 103
Sri Lanka: 94 253 / 591 / 28
Afghanistan: 57 019 / 2521 / 64
Maldives: 25 304 / 67 / 122
Bhutan: 900 / 1 / 1

Over the last 7 days, 757 411, 48 368, and 32 664 COVID-19 cases were detected in India, Bangladesh, and Pakistan, respectively, compared with 456 479, 33 369, and 32 809 cases in the preceding 7 days, revealing further escalation of the disease in India and Bangladesh but a stability trend in Pakistan. The number of total deaths attributed to COVID-19 in Pakistan has now crossed the mark of 15 000.

A total of 74 people died yesterday (8 Apr 2021) in Bangladesh due to COVID-19, the highest ever single-day count in the country since the 1st case detected on 8 Mar 2020. As many as 5 583 507 people have been vaccinated so far in the country with single dose of "Covishield" vaccine produced from the Serum Institute of India, which is the Oxford-AstraZeneca's COVID-19 vaccine. Administration of the 2nd dose of the same vaccine among the recipients of the 1st dose also started from yesterday (8 Apr 2021). A mass media report published recently referring to research findings has disclosed the circulation of B.1.1.7 (first detected in UK) and B.1.351 (first detected in South Africa) mutant variants in the country with the predominance (81%) of B.1.351 variant since the 4th week of March (2021) (see archive no. 20210408.8294842). The circulation of this more transmissible variant and the people's improper or noncompliance of personal and social safety guidelines could be the main reasons of the beginning of a new wave of the disease in the country after decreasing the daily case positivity of less than 3%.

The peak of COVID-19 in India in this new wave has already overtaken the highest peak observed in the 1st wave of the disease, and the new cases are still increasing alarmingly every day. The country reported a total of 131 918 new cases yesterday (8 Apr 2021) alone, the highest single-day record ever. India has also reported the introduction of the mutant variant B.1.1.7, and the circulation of a new "double mutant" variant whose progenitors seem to be the L452R strain, first detected in California, the United States, and the E484Q strain, which is reportedly circulating in India (see archive no. 20210325.8269014). There is seemingly no information from India on the introduction and circulation of the mutant B.1.351 in the country, unlike Bangladesh.

B.1.351 variant has multiple mutations in the spike protein, including K417N, E484K, N501Y. Currently there is no evidence to suggest that this variant has any impact on disease severity. There is some evidence to indicate that one of the spike protein mutations, E484K, may affect neutralization by some polyclonal and monoclonal antibodies (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/science/science-briefs/scientific-brief-emerging-variants.html).

Over the last 7 days, 1639 and 591 cases were reported from Nepal and Sri Lanka, respectively, indicating an increase trend of the disease in Nepal but a trend of stability in Sri Lanka, compared with the data from the previous week.

